Here's a simple HTML file that includes embedded CSS and JavaScript. This web app allows you to edit a JSON list. You can add, edit, and delete items from the list. 

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>JSON List Editor</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        #jsonList {
            margin-top: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            padding: 10px;
            max-width: 400px;
        }
        .item {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            margin: 5px 0;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            flex: 1;
            margin-right: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>JSON List Editor</h1>
<input type="text" id="newItem" placeholder="Add new item" />
<button onclick="addItem()">Add Item</button>

<div id="jsonList"></div>

<script>
    let jsonList = ["Item 1", "Item 2", "Item 3"];

    function renderList() {
        const listContainer = document.getElementById('jsonList');
        listContainer.innerHTML = '';
        jsonList.forEach((item, index) => {
            const itemDiv = document.createElement('div');
            itemDiv.className = 'item';
            itemDiv.innerHTML = `
                <input type="text" value="${item}" onchange="editItem(${index}, this.value)" />
                <button onclick="deleteItem(${index})">Delete</button>
            `;
            listContainer.appendChild(itemDiv);
        });
    }

    function addItem() {
        const newItemInput = document.getElementById('newItem');
        const newItem = newItemInput.value.trim();
        if (newItem) {
            jsonList.push(newItem);
            newItemInput.value = '';
            renderList();
        }
    }

    function editItem(index, value) {
        jsonList[index] = value;
    }

    function deleteItem(index) {
        jsonList.splice(index, 1);
        renderList();
    }

    // Initial render
    renderList();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The file contains a header, an input field for adding new items, and a div to display the JSON list.
- **CSS**: Basic styling is applied to make the list look organized.
- **JavaScript**: 
  - A JSON list is initialized with three items.
  - Functions are provided to render the list, add new items, edit existing items, and delete items.
  - The list is rendered initially when the page loads. 

You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see the JSON list editor in action.

